<subSubSection id="07A56518FFE34D21FF249CC8FC148DA6" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="4F003693FFE34D21FF249CC8FC148DA6" blockId="15.[123,652,868,1742]" lastBlockId="15.[699,1228,193,1301]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
DIAGNOSIS: Galeal comb present, albeit weak in the American clade of 
<taxonomicName id="88BF4D10FFE34D21FDBB9CD6FD358EE5" authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1898" box="[519,651,927,950]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Hesperapis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7DCBEA81FFE34D21FDBB9CD6FD358EE5" box="[519,651,927,950]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Hesperapis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and apomorphically reduced to about five bristles in a species of 
<taxonomicName id="88BF4D10FFE34D21FE2E9C90FF7A895E" authority="" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Eremaphanta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Popovapis">
<emphasis id="7DCBEA81FFE34D21FE2E9C90FD8E8EA3" box="[402,560,985,1008]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Eremaphanta</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="7DCBEA81FFE34D21FDF89C90FF06895D" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Popovapis</emphasis>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Scopa largely confined to outer surface of metatibia and metabasitarsus; inner metatibial surface with longitudinal median band of keirotrichia (scopal setae dense, long, minutely barbed, present on both inner and outer surfaces of metatibia and metabasitarsus, and keirotrichia absent in 
<taxonomicName id="88BF4D10FFE34D21FDBF9BEEFDC789ED" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[515,633,1191,1214]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Dasypoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7DCBEA81FFE34D21FDBF9BEEFDC789ED" box="[515,633,1191,1214]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Dasypoda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); metabasitibial plate present in female and nearly all males (apomorphically absent in some male 
<taxonomicName id="88BF4D10FFE34D21FEB69BB6FE308845" authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1898" box="[266,398,1279,1302]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Hesperapis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7DCBEA81FFE34D21FEB69BB6FE308845" box="[266,398,1279,1302]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Hesperapis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) (absent in 
<taxonomicName id="88BF4D10FFE34D21FD959BB7FF018860" authorityName="Borner" authorityYear="1919" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Dasypodaina">Dasypodaina</taxonomicName>
). Propodeal profile nearly horizontal at base (all more or less in same plane in 
<taxonomicName id="88BF4D10FFE34D21FDE29A70FF73883D" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Dasypoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7DCBEA81FFE34D21FDE29A70FF73883D" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Dasypoda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Male S1 with broad, transparent marginal zone with deep median cleft; lateroapical lobes of male S7 absent (present in other dasypodaines). Gonostylus usually short and broad, fully fused to gonocoxite (nearly always deeply bifid and well differentiated from gonocoxite by narrow, partly membranous area in 
<taxonomicName id="88BF4D10FFE34D21FE30996DFD978B68" authorityName="Borner" authorityYear="1919" box="[396,553,1572,1595]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Dasypodaina">Dasypodaina</taxonomicName>
). Larva with extreme reduction of cephalic and mouthpart structures; maxilla and labium fused; prementum and postmentum fused (
<bibRefCitation id="2B2E4B62FFE34D21FF3F99D0FE648BE3" author="Rozen, J. G., Jr. &amp; R. J. McGinley" box="[131,474,1689,1712]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="1 - 31" refId="ref23048" refString="Rozen, J. G., Jr., and R. J. McGinley. 1974. Phylogeny and systematics of Melittidae based on the mature larvae (Insecta, Hymenoptera, Apoidea). American Museum Novitates 2545: 1 - 31. [publ. date: 10 September 1974]" type="journal article" year="1974">Rozen and McGinley, 1974</bibRefCitation>
; Rozen, 1978; however, larvae of 
<taxonomicName id="88BF4D10FFE34D21FEDE99FEFDBE8B9D" authorityName="Popov" authorityYear="1940" box="[354,512,1719,1742]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Eremaphanta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7DCBEA81FFE34D21FEDE99FEFDBE8B9D" box="[354,512,1719,1742]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Eremaphanta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
remain un­ discovered and so validity of larval traits await confirmation).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="07A56518FFE34D21FD649FB5FB238804" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="4F003693FFE34D21FD649FB5FBF68846" blockId="15.[699,1228,193,1301]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
COMMENTS: 
<taxonomicName id="88BF4D10FFE34D21FCCE9FB5FBBD8C40" authorityName="Ascher and Engel" authorityYear="2005" box="[882,1027,252,275]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Hesperapina">Hesperapina</taxonomicName>
is herein proposed for 
<taxonomicName id="88BF4D10FFE34D21FC899E50FC078C63" authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1898" box="[821,953,281,304]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Hesperapis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="lato">
<emphasis id="7DCBEA81FFE34D21FC899E50FC078C63" box="[821,953,281,304]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Hesperapis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="66F857FAFFE34D21FC7F9E50FC5B8C63" box="[963,997,281,304]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" sensu="lato">s.l.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(i.e., 
<emphasis id="7DCBEA81FFE34D21FB919E50FBD08C63" box="[1069,1134,281,304]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">sensu</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="2B2E4B62FFE34D21FBCB9E50FC958C1E" author="Michener, C. D." pageId="15" pageNumber="16" refId="ref20489" refString="Michener, C. D. 2000. The Bees of the World. Baltimore: Johns Hopkins University Press, xiv 1 [1] 1 913 pp." type="book" year="2000">
<taxonomicName id="88BF4D10FFE34D21FBCB9E50FD5F8C1E" authority="ENGEL, 2005" authorityName="ENGEL" authorityYear="2005" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" status="new subtribe" subTribe="Michener">Michener</taxonomicName>
, 2000
</bibRefCitation>
, including subgenera 
<emphasis id="7DCBEA81FFE34D21FB929E7EFB278C1D" box="[1070,1177,311,334]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Capicola</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName id="88BF4D10FFE34D21FD079E1DFCE88C38" authorityName="Stage" authorityYear="1981" box="[699,854,340,363]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Xeralictoides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7DCBEA81FFE34D21FD079E1DFCE88C38" box="[699,854,340,363]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Xeralictoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; previously these taxa had been treated as separate genera, e.g., 
<bibRefCitation id="2B2E4B62FFE34D21FBEB9E38FD488CF6" author="Michener, C. D." pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="1 - 135" refId="ref20277" refString="Michener, C. D. 1981. Classification of the bee family Melittidae, with a review of the species of Meganomiinae. Contributions of the American Entomological Institute 18 (3): iii 1 1 - 135. [publ. date: 23 December 1981]" type="journal article" year="1981">
<taxonomicName id="88BF4D10FFE34D21FBEB9E38FB798CDB" authority="ENGEL, 2005" authorityName="ENGEL" authorityYear="2005" box="[1111,1223,369,392]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" status="new subtribe" subTribe="Michener">Michener</taxonomicName>
, 1981
</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="88BF4D10FFE34D21FC819EC6FC658CF5" authorityName="Popov" authorityYear="1940" box="[829,987,399,422]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Eremaphanta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7DCBEA81FFE34D21FC819EC6FC658CF5" box="[829,987,399,422]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Eremaphanta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The distribution of hesperapines is unique among bees and features remarkable disjunctions. Nearly all species occur in or near xeric or Mediterraneanclimate areas. In the Old World 
<taxonomicName id="88BF4D10FFE34D21FB919D4DFB758F48" authorityName="Popov" authorityYear="1940" box="[1069,1227,516,539]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Eremaphanta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7DCBEA81FFE34D21FB919D4DFB758F48" box="[1069,1227,516,539]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Eremaphanta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is restricted to xeric regions of Central Asia southwest to 
<collectingCountry id="37A87603FFE34D21FCD99D77FC2A8F06" box="[869,916,574,597]" name="Iran" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Iran</collectingCountry>
(subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="88BF4D10FFE34D21FB969D76FB1B8F05" box="[1066,1189,575,598]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Eremaphanta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Popovapis">
<emphasis id="7DCBEA81FFE34D21FB969D76FB1B8F05" box="[1066,1189,575,598]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Popovapis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to Baluchistan), while 
<taxonomicName id="88BF4D10FFE34D21FC049D15FB758F20" authority="" box="[952,1227,604,627]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Hesperapis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Capicola">
<emphasis id="7DCBEA81FFE34D21FC049D15FB828F20" box="[952,1084,604,627]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Hesperapis</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="7DCBEA81FFE34D21FBEB9D15FB7C8F20" box="[1111,1218,604,627]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Capicola</emphasis>
)
</taxonomicName>
and its sister subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="88BF4D10FFE34D21FC6B9D30FBCE8FC3" authorityName="Michener" authorityYear="1981" box="[983,1136,633,656]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Capicoloides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7DCBEA81FFE34D21FC6B9D30FBCE8FC3" box="[983,1136,633,656]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Capicoloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are restricted to xeric parts of 
<collectingCountry id="37A87603FFE34D21FC4B9DDFFB2D8FFE" box="[1015,1171,662,685]" name="South Africa" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">South Africa</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="37A87603FFE34D21FD079DFDFC9D8F98" box="[699,803,692,715]" name="Namibia" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Namibia</collectingCountry>
. The remaining subgenera of 
<taxonomicName id="88BF4D10FFE34D21FB289DFDFCAC8FBB" authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1898" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Hesperapis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7DCBEA81FFE34D21FB289DFDFCAC8FBB" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Hesperapis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are restricted to North America. Most species are found in seasonally dry habitats in the western 
<collectingCountry id="37A87603FFE34D21FC509C45FB2E8E70" box="[1004,1168,780,803]" name="United States of America" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">United States</collectingCountry>
and northwestern 
<collectingCountry id="37A87603FFE34D21FCE39C60FC028E13" box="[863,956,809,832]" name="Mexico" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Mexico</collectingCountry>
; the overall range extends from Oregon, North Dakota, and Illinois south to the Gulf Coast of Alabama and northwestern Florida and to 
<collectingRegion id="8D7BF871FFE34D21FBA99CC8FD5D8EE6" country="Mexico" name="Baja California Sur" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Baja California Sur</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion id="8D7BF871FFE34D21FC9E9CD7FC388EE6" box="[802,902,926,949]" country="Mexico" name="Morelos" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Morelos</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="37A87603FFE34D21FC299CD7FC508EE6" box="[917,1006,926,949]" name="Mexico" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Mexico</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="2B2E4B62FFE34D21FBBC9CD7FB018EE6" author="Michener, C. D." box="[1024,1215,926,949]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" refId="ref20489" refString="Michener, C. D. 2000. The Bees of the World. Baltimore: Johns Hopkins University Press, xiv 1 [1] 1 913 pp." type="book" year="2000">
<taxonomicName id="88BF4D10FFE34D21FBBC9CD7FBCC8EE6" authority="ENGEL, 2005" authorityName="ENGEL" authorityYear="2005" box="[1024,1138,926,949]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" status="new subtribe" subTribe="Michener">Michener</taxonomicName>
, 2000
</bibRefCitation>
). The only plausible explanation for the extreme disjunction between the three areas of hesperapine occurrence, which are not linked directly by geology, is extensive extinction of ancestral populations in intervening areas due to climatic deterioration (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation id="2B2E4B62FFE34D21FB3C9B07FD4489D0" author="Engel, M. S." pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="1 - 192" refId="ref16448" refString="Engel, M. S. 2001. A monograph of the Baltic amber bees and evolution of the Apoidea (Hymenoptera). Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 259: 1 - 192. [publ. date: 16 April 2001]" type="journal article" year="2001">
<taxonomicName id="88BF4D10FFE34D21FB3C9B07FB798936" authority="ENGEL, 2005" authorityName="ENGEL" authorityYear="2005" box="[1152,1223,1102,1125]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" status="tribus novum" tribe="Engel">Engel</taxonomicName>
, 2001
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="88BF4D10FFE34D21FCB29B25FC2189D0" authorityName="Ascher and Engel" authorityYear="2005" box="[782,927,1132,1155]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Hesperapina">Hesperapina</taxonomicName>
thus exhibits limited, relict distribution in three of Sclater’s biogeographic regions, whereas its sister group 
<taxonomicName id="88BF4D10FFE34D21FB239BEFFC8F8988" authorityName="Borner" authorityYear="1919" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Dasypodaina">Dasypodaina</taxonomicName>
is widely distributed across the Palearctic Region but absent from North America and sub­Saharan Africa.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4F003693FFE34D21FD559A09FB238804" blockId="15.[745,1181,1344,1368]" box="[745,1181,1344,1368]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<taxonomicName id="88BF4D10FFE34D21FD559A09FC498804" authority="Engel" authorityName="Engel" authorityYear="2005" box="[745,1015,1344,1368]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" status="new subtribe" subTribe="Macrogaleina">
<emphasis id="7DCBEA81FFE34D21FD559A09FC188805" bold="true" box="[745,934,1344,1368]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">MACROGALEINA</emphasis>
Engel
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel id="66F857FAFFE34D21FBB99A09FB238804" box="[1029,1181,1344,1367]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" rank="subTribe">new subtribe</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
